  "reason_thou": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs when
simplifycfg attempts to process an EH cleanupret. Specifically, the
assertion firing is in CleanupReturnInst::getCleanupPad(), which casts
operand 0 to CleanupPadInst. The backtrace shows this happens via
removeUnwindEdge called from removeEmptyCleanup/simplifyCleanupReturn, which
is the first transformation.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log
indicates that simplifycfg removes several unreachable blocks first (panic1,
funclet_bb14, unreachable). Notably, funclet_bb14 contains the defining
cleanuppad for a later cleanupret (bb13). After removing funclet_bb14,
subsequent transformations touch cleanupret/cleanup pads. The first
transformation point in the backtrace is removeUnwindEdge when simplifying a
cleanupret. The log aligns with this: simplifycfg starts cleaning up
predecessors/unwind edges, and the crash triggers when removeUnwindEdge
calls getCleanupPad().\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nremoveUnwindEdge has a
case for CleanupReturnInst that constructs a new cleanupret which
unwinds-to-caller: CleanupReturnInst::Create(CRI->getCleanupPad(), nullptr,
...). This relies on CRI->getCleanupPad(), which internally does
cast<CleanupPadInst>(Op<0>()). However, due to earlier unreachable block
deletion, the defining cleanuppad may have been erased, and the operand of
the cleanupret can transiently become undef (or otherwise no longer be a
CleanupPadInst). simplifyCleanupReturn already accounts for transient undef
operands with a guard: if (isa<UndefValue>(RI->getOperand(0))) return false;
But removeUnwindEdge does not; it unconditionally calls getCleanupPad() and
asserts.\n\nIn other words, removeUnwindEdge assumes operand 0 of a
CleanupReturnInst is always a CleanupPadInst, but simplifycfg can create a
state where it is undef before removeUnwindEdge runs. This mismatch causes
the assertion.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit Local.cpp in
removeUnwindEdge to avoid calling getCleanupPad() if operand 0 is no longer
a CleanupPadInst. Instead, use the raw operand, which can be undef, when
creating the new CleanupReturnInst. This mirrors simplifyCleanupReturn's
tolerance for undef and prevents the cast assertion.\n\nProposed change
(lines 2853-2861 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Utils/Local.cpp):\n- Current code:\n
if (auto *CRI = dyn_cast<CleanupReturnInst>(TI)) {\n    NewTI =
CleanupReturnInst::Create(CRI->getCleanupPad(), nullptr,
CRI->getIterator());\n    UnwindDest = CRI->getUnwindDest();\n  } else if
(...)\n\n- Replace with:\n  if (auto *CRI = dyn_cast<CleanupReturnInst>(TI))
{\n    // Operand 0 may be transiently undef if its defining cleanuppad was
deleted.\n    // Use the raw operand to preserve this state without
asserting.\n    Value *Pad = CRI->getOperand(0);\n    NewTI =
CleanupReturnInst::Create(Pad, nullptr, CRI->getIterator());\n    UnwindDest
= CRI->getUnwindDest();\n  } else if (...)\n\nRationale:\n-
CleanupReturnInst::Create accepts a Value* for the pad and asserts it is
non-null, but does not require it to be a CleanupPadInst at construction
time. Using the raw operand preserves undef values and avoids the cast in
getCleanupPad(). Subsequent code which might query getCleanupPad() already
contains guards (e.g., simplifyCleanupReturn) to skip processing when
operand 0 is undef.\n- This keeps removeUnwindEdge robust in the presence of
transient undef EH pad operands created by prior unreachable/dead block
deletion.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by removeUnwindEdge
assuming that the cleanuppad operand of a cleanupret is always a
CleanupPadInst and calling getCleanupPad(), while simplifycfg can create a
transient state where that operand becomes undef after deleting the defining
EH pad block. Updating removeUnwindEdge to construct the replacement
cleanupret using CRI->getOperand(0) instead of CRI->getCleanupPad() avoids
the invalid cast and aligns with existing simplifycfg logic that tolerates
undef EH pad operands. This fixes the assertion and allows simplifycfg to
proceed safely.",
